caption: Nice and interesting food, not exactly like Chinese street dishes but unique in a good way! Definitely filling, would love to see they have more vegetable options in the menu.

Excellent cocktails, both alcoholic and non-alcoholic, wonderful food, there are even vegetarian dishes. The prices are reasonable and the service is excellent. I use their no-contact delivery, I also like it.

Love this place. Good restaurant organization online is underrated. Great vegetarian food - dumplings esp with the sauce they put it in, fair prices. Good stuff with all the acceptance signs outside the store, gonna try their dumpling making kit soon.

We ordered dumplings, salad, and curry (plus a dozen eggs) for take-out. Each item was carefully packaged with instructions on how to warm/cook, which was very easy. Since we finished the cooking and heating process,  our food was actually warm and had texture since it wasn't sitting for 30 minutes before being served. The flavors were bold and well seasoned, but balanced. Everyone had a smile on while we picked up, great service. We are excited to try this again and see how they highlight different in season ingredients!

This place is great. Decided to stop in for a quick bite a while ago. I thought it was going to be the usual dumplings. This place serves large servings and you can taste the freshness every bite. Wish there were more options

I bought the Double Awesome cookbook at my local bookstore in Sisters, Oregon about six months ago. When I learned they were based in Boston, MA I knew that the next time I went to visit my finance's family in Franklin MA we would be going out of our way to eat here. We had the corn fitters (that dipping sauce is amazing), kale salad, dumpling sampler (omg pierogi!!), a green onion pancake sandwich, a house made honey tea, and the sticky rice dessert (out of this world). I have a lot of great things to say about Mei Mei, but what broke it for me was the fact that the house made pesto in the double awesome pancake sandwich tasted like (in the words of my friend) 'random greens half-blended with some oil and absolutely no basil'. It tasted nothing like pesto - I couldn't taste the basil or the pine nuts or the olive oil; in fact, it tasted mostly like ground up grass.  But. The staff were amazing, their side dishes were great - the curried sweet potato is especially 😍 - and reasonably priced, and the flavoured ketchup is 😍. The beef sandwich had a lovely flavour as well. Just don't get the double awesome.

Fast and friendly service. Amazing food! I got the perogi dumplings and they did not disappoint. Perfect crunchy texture and a great balance of flavors. Will be returning and making it a study spot for sure!

Delicious fusion food. The scallion pancakes are authentic and not the oily, overly deep fried kind. All the sandwich fillings are flavourful and well balanced with veg! Highly recommend the beef & broc.
Delicious food! Scallion pancake sandwich is beyond good!
Joined a learn to make Dumplings class and was pleasantly surprised by the experience- fun and  delicious!

On a recent trip to Boston, it was a great opportunity to check this place out after hearing about the food truck on social media and seeing Yotam Ottolenghi give his thumbs up.  It’s a pity this place didn’t appear on “Ugly Delicious” in its “Fried Rice” episode. It’s a great example of Chinese food evolving* beyond what is expected of it. (This is coming from a person who has worked in the Restaurant food supply chain and probably eaten too much Chinese food in their lifetime.)  We came as a group of 4 which was an opportunity to try as many things as possible: Carrot and Turnip cake Bluefish fritters Corn Fritters (a nice freebie as it was my first visit) Double Awesome scallion pancake Lemongrass and pork dumplings Cheese Pierogi Kale salad  Having said that, if you are a bit conservative about Chinese food or come with expectations of what “Chinese” food is, I’m guessing you are likely to be disappointed. It’s a place I wouldn’t be able to take my parents as they would probably moan at me as they have the quantity-over-quality mindset.  The staff were friendly and seem like a tight-knit team which is good to see.  It’s easy to picture London embracing a place like this. Scallion pancakes done this way could be the new “Bao”.  NB * The worst case of “evolving” I’ve seen is a Chinese supermarket/restaurant being given a lot of LKK’s newish Sriracha mayo on the cheap. Not knowing what to do with it, they smother a load of battered chicken with the damn stuff and is not a great combo with white rice.
Great food and cozy atmosphere, they changed the menu recently and I think for the better. Their scallion pancake sandwiches are as good as it gets.
Good food. While eating too much will feel not that so good?

(This review is for the food truck)  I found Mei Mei to be a decent lunch truck.  The food was certainly tasty, it just had a few flaws that give this truck an "A-OK" rating in my book.  The Chorizard (play on "Charizard"?) is a bowl with chorizo, black beans, and carrots, topped with feta and fried shallots.  The chorizo was flavorful, juicy and savory.  The pickled carrots cut through the savory chorizo with a vinegary tang.  The apple dressing that covers everything in the bowl is a good source of tangy flavor; the black beans need that extra kick, and the apple dressing helps deliver it.  Unfortunately, I found almost no fried shallots.  Towards the end of my meal, I found one sitting at the bottom of the bowl and thought to myself, "Oh right, there were supposed to be fried shallots in here".  A big handful of fried shallots would have given a nice salty crunch, I missed them here.  The black beans were hit-or-miss.  Some were cooked great, but some were still a little hard.  They didn't seem to have much seasoning on them, and were a little bland eaten on their own.  The biggest issue I had, was that the bowl felt incomplete:  there wasn't any rice, or some big base ingredient.  It felt like I was eating all of the toppings to a rice bowl, just without the rice.  Since it was missing a good base, it wasn't as much food as I'd like.  The prices are a little steep for the amount of food you get.  All in all, I'll visit Mei Mei every now and then if I'm looking for a lighter lunch.
Reasonable price, very close to Fendway, they'll modify the menu if you're on a special diet.

Meimei is always a very solid food experience -- they recently switched to an all-day counter service only menu, and expanded their scallion pancake sandwich offerings. Ordered the beef & broc the other day with oozy egg, which was very tasty although a little undersalted. The turnip cakes were nice and spicy, and less oily than the version you'd see at a dimsum place. The spicy ketchup is one of my favorite sauces at Meimei so make sure to slather your sandwiches in that. All in all, a great casual, quick lunch spot!

Our host made exceptional recommendations, but our favorite was definitely the double awesome. We’re also a sucker for dumplings and those were also delicious. Can’t go wrong with anything you order. Mei Mei has some amazing dishes, but my favorite is the Double Awesome w/ Cottage Bacon. The staff here is nice and efficient. This is one of my go-to lunch and brunch spots in Boston. Only drawback, they are closed Mondays.

So excited they are on Seated! The food was delicious, especially the double awesome. The atmosphere and servers were great and our food came out in a timely manner. The style and execution of the food was very creative. Overall, it was great! I would definitely go again!

The restaurant was set up nicely, but the food itself was just okay. It's probably because I'm not a huge asian fusion fan (I prefer authentic asian cuisine), but their dumplings are under-seasoned. The scallion sandwiches do look delicious though. It probably appeals more to the local Boston crowd.

good if you like interesting asian fusion which can definitely be hit or miss. It's more pricey than what is described by google

Great food. Everything on the menu is delicious. I especially like the double awesome. Good beer selection as well. Had a good curry bowl as well. On my,last visit hey had a special from 2pm to 5pm where you get free corn fritters with the purchase of a beer, which was great. It is cool to see a place that has their food locally sourced

The server recommended 2-3 dishes per person for a full meal so we ordered 8 dishes (2 per person). We ordered the dim sum turnip cakes, sweet corn fritters, ginger-scallion kale salad, cumin lamb and three sisters dumplings, rib tips with miso-caramel brussel sprouts, mapo goat noodles and harvest moon curry. The dishes were very small for the price. We only got 3-4 dumplings/fritters and a small bowl of noodles. The cumin lamb dumplings were amazing while the rib tips were a bit salty.  The others were mediocre. We also ordered the maple creme brûlée, carrot cake churros and s’mores. The brûlée wasn’t warm when it came out but it was well caramelized. The churros were unique-hint of sourness but sweet. The s’more was an incredibly sweet brownie with toasted marshmallows, graham crumbs and a few mint leaves.  We were quite hungry after the main dishes but the desserts were filling. Our total was $110. the dishes were great but incredibly pricey. Unique take on Chinese cuisine.

Everything is fried here. Maybe I should have realized if I had looked at the menu before. Dumpling were meh. If you like fried food, come here. If you like more authentic Chinese dumplings, go elsewhere!
Maybe our favorite place in the city. Creative takes on Chinese food, all of which are reasonably priced and addictively delicious.

You just cannot go wrong when you order a double awesome and corn fritters. Still venture into the neighborhood just to order Mei Mei.

Creative modern takes on Chinese and Korean classics. The three sisters vegetarian dumplings are surprisingly tasty and satisfying, even for this carnivore. And for the homesick Ithacans out there, you can get your Piggery pig dog fix here!
Consistently amazing. Always exciting to try their creative new seasonal dishes and variations. Very friendly and helpful staff as well.
Great food, great atmosphere, attentive service. Always happy and full leaving.
One of our go to places since their food truck stopped in front of our apartment. Do the double awesome and sweet corn fritters, you won't be disappointed.
The food is delicious, but the price is way too high for the amount of food you get.
The curry was the best. Don't get the chicken, overpriced & tasted like dog food.

Mei Mei has some of the most interesting and innovative food in the northeast at student prices.  If you want James Beard quality at rock bottom prices, this is the best (and only) place you can go.  If I only ate here and at The Lost Kitchen for the rest of my life, I would have a great life.  Thanks, Mei Mei!

Nice

The double awesome is supposedly their signature dish but the kimchi dog is the hands down winner in my book. The double awesome would have felt a little incomplete without one of the add on proteins (turkey, ham or bacon). The "Double Awesome" is amazing! Try the ketchup/hot sauce mix in the plastic squeeze bottle on it. It sounds a little weird, but it is great.

I like the ice cream dessert a lot!! The main course is just OK
Good. Some dishes are great. Overall pretty uneven.

Nothing to write home about.
Asian fusion. Exquisite food! Excellent staff.
Very yummy. Wowed by the lamb and coriander dumplings. Small, warm space feels a bit cafeteria-like. Good service.
Great, cute dishes overflowing with flavor!

Brick-and-mortar outlet of popular food truck serving innovative Asian food. Their food truck cross-overs are exceptional but some of their more substantial dishes feel like they are missing something.
Try the scallion pancake sandwiches... your only regret will be not to have tried them before
Super friendly and local!

Good food, nicely massaged kale for the kale salad with oozy egg. Love the locally sourced produce and pastured meats. But 14 bucks for 4 dumplings and the prices in general were outrageous. Nice if you're not buying or are earning six figures.
Pretty good food!
Lots of delicious bites to eat here. Decent, small wine and beer situation. Hard to get a seat sometimes.
A bit pricey but great food with creative options and local products including beers.
This restaurant offers minuscule portions of food whose quality does not merit its exorbitant prices.

The dishes are well-considered and absolutely delicious, but don't come here if you are hungry. The portions are tapas-sized. We spent $100 for 3 people with a beer each and had to stop at Jimmy John's next door afterward to fill up..
Interesting...
This place is incredible. You can have very delicious lunch for under $10. Absolutely recommending it.
Asian fusion that is slightly overpriced. The taste is unique, but leaves me yearning for traditional Chinatown fare.

Such a friendly little restaurant.  Their brand of fusion isn't forced at all, but feels natural and experimental.  Apparently the owners are Chinese-American.  They grew up eating steamed buns, hot dogs and everything in between, so they made a menu which has both.  They also had one of the few spicy cocktail which I ever found to be successful the spicy notes didn't stick out but blended with the flavor of the drink.

Interesting menu. The items I tried were both unique and tasty. Corn fritters with sirracha aioli was pretty good. The scallion pancake sandwich mostly tasted like the breakfast items in it, and so the scallion pancake itself was not too noticeable but it was still pretty good.

Mei Mei does everything right.  First of all the food -  I love their commitment to locally sourced meats and seasonal produce. Unique, but simple preparations really let the ingredients shine. The addition of halloumi cheese in the spring green curry was a great move.  The service is perfect - warm, welcoming, polite, friendly, unobtrusive but right there when you need anything.  The atmosphere is relaxed - in terms of both dress and how it makes me feel. Somehow it is casual enough to bring a baby, but refined enough to bring a date. I don't know how they manage it, but they do.  Don't forget to check out the floor in the bathroom.

Mei Mei has fun, inventive food. The dessert was so unusual and playful with a mix of green tea and honey flavors and many different textures. The rice porridge is incredible--flavorful meat and warm, cozy rice porridge to moderate the intense flavors of the meat. Pumpkin fritters were good, but not amazing, but that is a tiny negative when considering how good the rest of the food was.

One of the best things you can get for lunch is a Mei Mei Double Awesome. Eggs, pesto, greens, cheese and all locally sourced. Do yourself a favor and get it with pastrami too, it's worth it. I've never had anything from Mei Mei that wasn't really good.
Funky, fun food. Very creative and well made.  I'm mad about the dumplings and the selection of sauces. So good!

Mei Mei's is one of my favorite restaurants in Boston. I first fell in love when I had their Double Awesome, a scallion pancake sandwich with a poached then fried egg, pesto, and cheddar cheese. You can also have it with bacon. And I don't know how they manage this, but it's the best bacon I've ever had.  They have a lot of interesting dishes on their menu, that I never would have thought of eating before. But trust them and try new things. All of the things I've had were delicious, even if I wasn't familiar with the ingredients.  What keeps me going back besides the food is the service. They're very friendly and some of them even remember things that are going on in my life and ask me about it.  I just wish they had more locations. But hopefully they will soon!

Mei Mei street kitchen is pretty phenomenal. I've only attended the brick and mortar version a couple of times and its always been quite a treat. The double awesome is about the best breakfast anytime sandwich I can imagine. Scallion pancake sandwich, you're doing gods work Mei Mei.  On top of some really solid choices Mei Mei also does some really out there and interesting experiments with food. Wheat berry salad with caramel brittle on top, whoa. The drink that has a lot of apple cider vinegar. Double whoa.  I wish it was just a tad cheaper, I always seem to spend more than I expect when I go. And once they told me that one of the sandwiches was no longer in season except it was the one with beets... and beets had just STARTED to be in season so it sort of threw me off.  Not a big deal, I still love Mei Mei and will continue to eat their delicious foods

Mei Mei's foodtruck is my usual go-to whenever I'm at SOWA.  Food is always spot on and the people working the truck are super friendly and upbeat. My number one favorite dish has to be the curry nachos. It seems like such a strange comb but it just works on so many levels. Flavors are perfect and the dish itself doesn't feel heavy.  I've heard great things about the Double Awesome though haven't had a chance to work up the nerve to give up my staple. MY friends, however, can vouch for it.

I love the vibe of this place. Most BU campus restaurants skimp on service and quality simply because it's catered to college students. They completely transformed the old restaurant and created a trendy, NYC modern Asian fusion vibe.  I got the double awesome with pastrami, and there were so many flavors. The scallion pancake wasn't too oily and the pesto and eggs added a great touch to the entire sandwich. It's a unique sandwich you won't be able to find anywhere else!  Their bathrooms are so clean, they smell good and have cute decor. That says a lot since usually bathrooms suck around the area.
Super flakey scallion pancake makes for the best sandwich ever. Full of flavor and texture without weighing you down.

I like the vibes here! This food truck favorite is now also indoors within a potential Restaurant Row at Park Drive and Buswell, Audubon Circle. My favorite, from the between-hours menu, was the Porco Rosso ($9), a scallion pancake sandwich with deli ham, cranberry hoisin, ginger-scallion ricotta and spring greens. Unexpectedly in 2nd place on my nascent ranking was the famous, modestly-named Double Awesome ($7) scallion pancake sandwich with local greens pesto, VT cheddar & 2 slow-poached-then-fried eggs; good--- but the runny eggs produced a rather doughy pancake. The scallion pancakes are not made in-house. By the way, those patrons who are hard up for the other kind of dough might be tempted to  excavate the trove of pennies firmly embedded within the restroom floor. After a few months of excavation, they may be able to afford a down payment on the $32 Bavette Steak.
Very tasty, fresh, a friendly space - and a good deal too.

I went to Mei Mei on a dinner date, the place is trendy and very well decorated. It's a small restaurant and not too formal. It has an uplifting ambiance and is well lit. I had the beef heart tartare and the nutella biscuit dessert. Both were spectacular! The owner has been there both times I have and is very attentive. A very pleasant experience.
Tasty, nice portions, creative dishes.
